dcterms:creator: W. H. Kersting
dcterms:description: The IEEE-123 Node Feeder System is a radial distribution test feeder used for simulating various fault conditions in power systems. It consists of 85 nodes with both overhead and underground lines, designed to facilitate the study of fault detection, localization, and classification.
dcterms:title: IEEE-123 Node Feeder System

dcterms:creator: R. C. Dugan
T. E. McDermott
dcterms:description: OpenDSS is an open-source platform used for simulating power distribution systems. It serves as a power flow equation solver and is utilized in this research for generating datasets related to fault events in distribution systems.
dcterms:title: OpenDSS

G. Alirezaei
R. Mathar
dcterms:description: The IEEE-13 Bus System is a standard test system used for evaluating fault detection and classification methods in power systems. It consists of 13 buses and is commonly used in machine learning applications for fault diagnosis.
dcterms:title: IEEE-13 Bus System

dcterms:creator: W. Li
D. Deka
dcterms:description: The IEEE-37 Bus System is utilized for real-time fault location studies in power distribution systems. It includes 37 buses and is often used in conjunction with machine learning techniques for fault diagnosis.
dcterms:title: IEEE-37 Bus System

dcterms:creator: W. Li

dcterms:description: The IEEE-39 Bus System is a benchmark for testing fault localization and PMU placement in power systems. It consists of 39 buses and is frequently used in deep learning applications for fault detection.
dcterms:title: IEEE-39 Bus System

dcterms:description: The IEEE-68 Bus System is used for fault classification and location studies in power distribution networks. It consists of 68 buses and is applied in various machine learning frameworks for fault diagnosis.
